04705nam a22006255i 9780226142425DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802261424257 a10.7208/97802261424252doi  a(DE-B1597)524904  a(OCoLC)812510406  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aLC205b.D46 2009eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a373.1826/222221 aDemerath, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProducing Success :bThe Culture of Personal Advancement in an American High School /cPeter Demerath. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b9 halftones, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction:Producing Success -- tPart One. Community, Home, and School Settings -- t1. The Wilton Way: Middle-Class Culture and Practice -- t2. Parental Support, Intervention, and Policy Manipulation -- t3. The Role of the School: Institutional Advantaging -- tPart Two. Student Identity and Practice -- t4. Identities for Control and Success: The Acquisition of Psychological Capital -- t5. Teaching the “Point-Hungry” Student: Hypercredentialing in Practice -- tPart Three. Costs of Personal Advancement -- t6. “Generation Stress” and School Success -- t7. Alienation, Marginalization, and Incivility -- t8. Conclusions -- tAppendix: WBHS 2002 Student Survey -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMiddle- and upper-middle-class students continue to outpace those from less privileged backgrounds. Most attempts to redress this inequality focus on the issue of access to financial resources, but as Producing Success makes clear, the problem goes beyond mere economics. In this eye-opening study, Peter Demerath examines a typical suburban American high school to explain how some students get ahead. Demerath undertook four years of research at a Midwestern high school to examine the mercilessly competitive culture that drives students to advance. Producing Success reveals the many ways the community’s ideology of achievement plays out: students hone their work ethics and employ various strategies to succeed, from negotiating with teachers to cheating; parents relentlessly push their children while manipulating school policies to help them get ahead; and administrators aid high performers in myriad ways, even naming over forty students “valedictorians.” Yet, as Demerath shows, this unswerving commitment to individual advancement takes its toll, leading to student stress and fatigue, incivility and vandalism, and the alienation of the less successful. Insightful and candid, Producing Success is an often troubling account of the educationally and morally questionable results of the American culture of success.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAcademic achievementxUnited States. 0aAcademic achievementzUnited States. 0aEducational sociologyxUnited States. 0aEducational sociologyzUnited States. 0aHigh schoolsxUnited States. 0aHigh schoolszUnited States. 0aMiddle classxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxUSAxElectronic books. 0aMiddle classzUnited States. 0aSocial stratificationxUnited States. 0aSocial stratificationzUnited States. 0aStudentsxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aStudentszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226142425423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226142425.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Pr